Hot spring, asphyxiation - USA (California) 20000927.1674
[1
Date: 28 Sep 2000
From: Aaron Hicks <osp001@hotmail.com>

[From the previous ProMED-mail post--Although carbon dioxide levels may
accumulate and be the cause of death, sulfur is what smells of rotten
eggs. - Mod.TG
More precisely, sulfur dioxide is the smell of rotten eggs, and it is
common to volcanic emissions. It is toxic, with an IDLH [Immediately
Dangerous to Life and Health concentration of 100 parts per million
(ppm); its odor is noticeable at 3-5 ppm, but the sense of smell is
desensitized at higher levels.
It is worth noting that the "Killer Lake of Cameroon" (Lake Nyos, in
Zimbabwe) killed at least 1746 people and thousands of cattle up to 20 km
distant in 1986 when it released a large volume of carbon dioxide gas.
Due to the depth of the lake (about 610'), large concentrations of carbon
dioxide gas dissolve in the depths. Vertical stratification in conjunction
with an absence of turnover found in temperate regions thanks to seasonal
changes permits the accumulation of large quantities of carbon dioxide gas.
When the layers are disturbed (landslide, etc.), the gas can erupt like an
uncorked champagne bottle. Local topography channeled the dense gas,
asphyxiating people while they slept.
Lake Nyos and Lake Monoun have been shown to accumulate dissolved carbon
dioxide thanks to a volcanic source, and efforts are underway to release
the gas in a controlled manner to prevent future incidents.
Unfortunately, funding is scant, and the research is not only
experimental but potentially dangerous.
--
AJ Hicks
OSG/PML Labs
Chandler, AZ
<osp001@hotmail.com>
