[2
Date: 29 Sep 2000
From: Parry, Dr. Michael <michael_parry@stamhosp.chime.org>

This sounds very strange. Are you sure it's CO2 that's the culprit?
Increased FiCO2 will trigger an intense hyperventilation response which
would drive the bather out of the spring to seek more air (that is lower
ambient CO2 concentrations). The ventilatory response to CO2 is usually
so strong that it is a test done in some PFT labs.
--
Michael F. Parry, M.D.
The Stamford Hospital
Professor of Clinical Medicine
Columbia University College of Physicians & Surgeons
New York, N.Y.
<michael_parry@stamhosp.chime.org>
