[3
Date: 29 Sep 2000
From: Richard T. Nicolls <rnicolls@sos.net>

The smell of sulfur in this report suggests that there may be low levels
of H2S [hydrogen sulfide present. Should the levels occasionally exceed
50 parts per million (ppm), it would explain the deaths. Has anyone
checked that out?
The previous erection of a higher wall around the spring could elevate
the levels of H2S as well as the CO2.
--
R.T. Nicolls, M.D.
<rnicolls@sos.net>
