[4
Date: Fri, 29 Sep 2000 15:08:48 +1200
From: Gail Irwin <irwin@ihug.co.nz>

As the moderator noted, the rotten egg smell is associated with sulphur -
most likely as hydrogen sulfide gas which is extremely poisonous. In
Rotorua, New Zealand, there have been a number of deaths associated with
hydrogen sulphide gas from thermal activity. Surely hydrogen sulfide
trapped by the brick wall is the more likely culprit in the Northern
Californian deaths?
--
Gail Irwin
New Zealand
<irwin@ihug.co.nz>

[As has been mentioned, the aspect of carbon dioxide is suspiciously
incorrect. Also, the smell of sulfur, or that of rotten eggs, would indeed
indicate the presence of hydrogen sulfide. I hope we will be getting more
definitive information from California. Until such is forthcoming, this
thread is cut. - Mod.TG
